{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945081401/0447.xml":{"full_text":"The Best ,Peace Argument\nMore *l*lanne<l Economy*\nXTAVING brought on a needless\nn FOOD SHORTAGE in the\nUnited States by inept bureaucratic\nmethods, the Office of Price Adminis\ntration is now proceeding in a similar\nway to cause a JOB SHORTAGE\nwhen the Pacific war ends and mil\nlions of veterans and war workers\nwill seek re-employment in private\nindustry.\nAs in the case of the meat famine,\nOPA is accomplishing its results\nthrough its arbitrary control of retail\nprice ceilings.\nThe policy was announced last\nMay in a statement which began:\n\u201c4 reconversion pricing program\nunder which most peacetime goods\nreturning to the market will sell at\n1942 retail prices was outlined by\nPrice Administrator Chester\nBowles\nHowever, it is no longer possible\nfor industry to operate on or near a\n1942 price basis.\n\n'THE reason is this\u2014under federal\nA regulation, wages and costs of\nmaterials have been greatly in\ncreased since 1941 and\u2014with virtu\nally all industries engaged in war\nproduction\u2014there have been no cor\nresponding price increases in the\nnormal market.\nThe average price of raw ma\nterials has gone up over 35 per cent\nsince 1941.\nBasic wages have been increased\nalmost 35 per cent.\nIn the same period, manufactur\ners have received an average price\nincrease of only 13 per cent.\nManufacturers resuming peace\ntime production will have to pay the\n1945 rates for labor and supplies; and\nthe 1942 scale of retail prices, at\nwhich their goods must be sold, will\nnot return enough to meet the costs\nof production.\nManufacturing and selling goods\non such terms\u2014at a loss on every\ntransaction\u2014amounts to giving mer\nchandise away, and no industrial\nconcern can operate and maintain\npay rolls in that way.\nThis precarious situation which,\nunless it be promptly corrected, may\nmean a postwar depression and bread\nlines as soon as Japan surrenders\u2014\nis not unknown to Congress.\n\nIT WAS brought to the attention of\nthe Lower House by Rep. Law\nrence H. Smith of Wisconsin on\nJuly 18.\n\u201cAt the present time,\" Mr. Smith\nBaid. the automotive industry, along\nwith hundreds of other firms are at\ntempting to convince the OPA that a\nsensible program for pricing new\ncars must be adopted if that indus\ntry is to produce the cars authorized\nby WPB.\n8-C\nTHE DETROIT TIMES\n\u201cProduction means employment,\nbut these essentials are geared to\nprice\n\u201cAutomobile manufacturers are\nnot interested in producing motor\ncars just for the sake of making\nthem.\n\u201cIn this industry, OPA insists\nupon a price formula which limits\nincreases in retail ceilings to about\n10 per cent above the prices in 1942.\n\u201cTo insist upon such a formula\nevidences a lack of appreciation for\nthe problems involved and, if they\npersist WILL RESULT IN UNEM\nPLOYMENT.\n\u201cOne more example of short\nsighted policy in this connection will\nsuffice\n*7 refer to the radio industry, a\nmost important field for develop\nment in the postwar period.\n\u201cRadio manufacturers have\nserved notice on OPA that THEY\nCANNOT OPERATE if present ceil\nings are to prevail.\n\u201cSome adjustment, they main\ntain, in retail prices must be made or\nPLANS FOR RECONVERSION\nWILL HAVE TO BE DELAYED.\n\u201cIn this event, thousands of\nworkers who have been looking to\nthis field will be compelled to seek\nwork elsewhere.\n\u201cLikewise s thousands of returned\nsoldiers and sailors cannot count\nupon this industry for jobs.\n\u201cI am reliably informed that the\nradio industry submitted plans a\nyear ago to OPA for reconversion.\n\u201cBut as usual, THIS AGENCY\nFAILED TO ACT.\n\u201cIt has treated this, and other\nindustries, as it has the food indus\ntry, and we will get the same result\nhere as presently prevails in food.\u201d\n\nI'IESPITE the warning, Congress\ndid nothing.\nThe House of Representatives re\ncessed for a long summer vacation,\nleaving the bureaucrats unwatched.\nAnd evidently the bureaucrats\nhave found in the postwar problem\nof re employment another opportu\nnity to undermine the profit system\non which free enterprise is sustained.\nRep. Smith noted, in his speech in\nConeress, that Price Administrator\nBowies has said \u201cindustry will have\nto absorb the costs\u201d of reconversion.\n\u201cThe argument by OPA said the\ncongressman, \u201cis that all business\nhas profited by the war, and they\ncan now afford to work for no profit.\n\u201cIt is a nonsensical position and\nwholly unrealistic.\n\u201cIt can only mean U N EMPLOY\nMENT FOR MILLIONS OF WORK\nERS because business firms will\nclose their doors if they cannot make\nA REASONABLE RETURN on in\nvested capital\nAug. 1945\nPaix\n>IALLOX\n\u2014Behind\nThe News\nWASHINGTON. Aug IS A\npeculiar uprising being\nbestirred within the Truman\ngovernment.\nAlttrough all polls agree the\nnew president's popularity is\ngreater than the late Mr.\nRoosevelt's at its uppermost\npeak, the remaining arch-New\nHeal politicos in the Senate are\ntrying to get a backfire or\nganized against him vvith left\nwing labor.\nSince the Rritish election*\ngave them spiritual inspiration\nthey no longer conceal their\nunhappiness with current\nevents\nThey are beginning to issue\nwarnings, contrive pressures\nand even create forebodings of\npolitical disaster.\nUp to now they have been\nacting with subtle indirection,\nas if they did not want to he\ncaught at it.\nNow they are more openly\ntrying a comeback, letting\npeople who carry tale* to the\nWhite House know how they\nfeel.\nThe trouble is Mr. Truman\nhas achieved unity in this coun\ntry, and they do not like it. As\none of their self-professed lead\ners expressed it to a newsman:\n\u201cMr. Truman i\u00bb for the Roose\nvelt philosophy all right, hut he\ndoe* not fight for It. We\u2019ve got\nto have fighting.\u201d\n0 0\nTV HAT particular thing they\nwant to fight for, they do\nnot specify or Know.\nMatters mention are a fairly\ncomplete disclosure of the re\nstricted character of the move\nment.\nThe New Dealers are not get\nting their friends appointed to\nfederal judgeships. Mr. Truman\nhas been choosing judges for\niegal and Democratic party rea\nson, rather than for their zeal\nin a socializing way.\nFurthermore they take the\ncabinet changes as a personal\nreflection on the New Deal, al\nthough every new member is a\npro-Roosevelt Democrat.\nIt is true the new appointees\nhave shown no inclination to in\nspire political hates, to fan up\nhot. if artificial issues; and hell\nraising is an indispensible part\n\u2014say the New Dealers\u2014of New\nDealism as they understand it.\nWithout mobilization of press\nure groups, accusations against\nthe motives of others and at\ntacking a disagreeing person as\na Fascist\" or something, like\nthe Communists do, these peo\nple think they will lose their\npower.\n\nSO prohpesies are being offered\nin the higher senatorial cir\ncles that a New Deal-CIO press\nure movement will force Mr.\nTruman to change by fall, and\ncause him to set up some en\nmities of some kind, to get the\nradical vote in the November\ncongressional elections.\nThey say he must have \"the\nlabor vote.\" that socialism has\nborn popular in Britain and\nthus there will he a development\nknown among Rooseveltlans as\n\u201ca swing to the left\" in the im\nmediate future.\nI doubt it The New Deal\ngame is pretty well played out.\nThese old devices are familiar\nto the people.\nThey no longer pay much at\ntention to such things.\nNeither Is \"the labor vote a*\na whole\nMr Roosevelt would not have\nwon the last election if the na\ntion had not been in the middle\nof war.\nHis radical following would\nnot hav e been sufficient to swing\nthe country\nThe people of this country\nare just as weary of n years\nof political hates and synthetic\nstrife tho British were of the\nconservatives.\n(Only a third of the new\u00ab\nlabor MPs have union member\nship and the hulk of labor s vic\ntory came from middle class,\nwhite collar districts where the\neffects of Britain's totally weak\nposition, economically, finan\ncially, materially and militar\nily. have been felt\n\nBritain is going down, this\ncountry is going up.\nThere was no hope for social\nism in the Canadian elections\nalmost Simultaneous with Bri\ntain's.\nThis budding Co-operative\nCommonwealth Federation was\nextinguished.\nIt elected only one MP and\nhe renounced his party affilia\ntion within two weeks, so now\nthere is not a single Socialist,\nmember of the Canadian Par\nliament\nConditions there are more like\nmils\nMr Truman is building up the\nDemocratic party to terrific\npow er\nMr Roosevelt relied on the\nCIO-PAC and similar radical\npressure groups to do his cam\npaigning\nMr. Truman is creating his\nown party organization.\nGive him three more years at\nit, and he may have an unbeat\nable organization like the Re\npublicans had for so many years\nif he has not achieved it al\nready.\nConsequently I do not look\nfor a change.\nWith unity and Truman as\npopular as both are, and Post\nmaster General Rob Hannegan\nbuiWing up a political organi\nzation. which they sav is hotter\nalready than .hm Farley had.\nthe appetites of the left-over\nNew Deal senators for patron\nage may go unappeased and the\nbackfires and pressures of the\nsmall left-w ing class group*, may\nhe wasted\nDU'clbutH t>* Klni frttM.rs Srnd Int\nThese\nDays\n\u2014George E.\nSokolsky\nnations in human history\nhave moved as far forward\nin a short time as Japan.\nAn isolated, hermit kingdom,\nwith hardly a contact with the\nreM of the world as recently as\n1852, Japan by 1917 was one of\nthe principal nations of the\nearth, the leader in Asia, the\nally of the victors of World War\n1. No country in Asia had so\nswiftly captured the sciences of\nthe went; none had discovered\nthe u*os of the military, indus\ntrial, financial and political\npower.\nOf all the nations in the east\nof Asia. Japan was the only one\nthat was completely sovereign.\nAll this was heady wine to a\nsmall country of hardly any re\nsources and limited man-power.\nIt made an already proud peo\nple over-bearing, vain-glorious\nand incapable of an objective\nappraisal of their relative posi\ntion in the world.\nJapan, at the end of World\nWar I tried to fill two areas\nwhich were without permanent\ngovernments. Russia and China.\nRut Russia soon regained her\nstrength and was able not only\nto push the Japanese out of\nSiberia hut by 1925, to attempt\nthe conquest of China by revo\nlution.\nChina never achieved either\nunity or power, but by a spirit\nual upsurge, by ingenius diplom\nacy and the indomitable person\nality of Chiang Kai-Shek, proved\nunconquerable.\nJapan tried bribery, chican\nprv. friendliness, racial homo\ngenity, war. Everything failed.\n\nr P r THE United States, Japan\nwas deeply indebted\nIt was Commodore Perry who\nopened that country to the\nworld\nIt was John Hay who stopped\nRussian aggression in Man\nchuria.\nIt was Theodore Roosevelt\nwho sa\\ed Japan in the Russo-\nJapanese war and by the Treaty\nof Portsmouth.\nIt was American loans that\nbuilt Japan's industry.\nIt was American purchases of\nraw silk that stabilized Japan s\nindustry and commerce.\nRut Japan and the United\nStates in the second decade of\nthis century fell afoul of each\nother on the racial issue.\nWestern states passed legis\nlation which, in effect, declared\nthe Japanese to be racially an\ninferior people.\nOur immigration laws placed\nthem in a category which they\nregarded as contemptuous.\nIt was this more than any\nother cause which turned Japan\ninto the wolf of the Orient.\n0\nIN RECENT decades the Japa\nnese have felt that they were\nbeing hemmed in on all sides\u2014\nRussia from the north. America\nfrom the west through China,\nAmerica from the east, and\nGreat Rritam from the south.\nCuriously enough. Japan was\nnot hemmed in at all.\nThe markets of all nations\nwore open to her industries and\nthe Japanese were prospering\nby the sale of cheaper manu\nfactured goods.\nAs a matter of faet, in many\nRntish colonies, particularly in\nIndia and Egypt and in North\nAfrica the Japanese were prog\nressing so rapidly that for years\ntheir trade was pressing upon\nthat of Great Britain.\nNo statistics, no facts could\noff-et the desire for possessions,\nfor equality with the United\nSlates.\nNothing tangible could rrplarp\nthe fear of Soviet Russia which\nhad taken control of Mongolia,\nwas moving into Turkestan and\nwould sooner or later, the Japa\nnese were sure, come again into\nManchuria.\n\n0\u201c N SEPT. 19. 1931. the Jap\nanese seized the Chinese\nthree eastern provinces, called\nManchuria\nSince then Japan has been\nat war with the world.\nUrn in (ianip\nr.U* KiiMfll 10 f\u00abr *\u00bbrh rorr-rl \u00bbn\n--\u00bb\u00bb*r throiilh *|U*\u00bbllnn \u00bbl*. 20 rich Inr\nth* rrmalnlnc l\u00bbn' qlirMlon* Any trorf OS\nnr hifhrr I* mrllrnl\nI\u2014What have James Stewart,\nGary Cooper. James Cagney\nand Paul Lukas in common,\nbesides being movie actors?\n2 Unscramble these noted\nAmericans of Hie past and\ntheir occupations: Ring W.\nI.ardner, educator; Francis\nScott Key. jurist; George\nEastman, poet, Oliver W.\nHolmes, inventor, Emma\nWillard, humorist.\n3 True or fates: <a) Wellesley\nis the women's college that\nhas the tradition of the\nDaisy chain <h\u00bb Technoc\nracy. which caused a stir in\n1932-33, hoped to see the\npower of government in the\nhands of scientists and en\ngineers.\n3\u2014ln speed racing for automo\nbiles why must a driver take\nas his record the average of\ntwo runs\u2014one in each direc\ntion and both within the\nhour\u2019\n5 Whifh of the great classical\ncomposers had hisjrareer cut\nshort by deafness?\n6 If someone called you an in\ntrovert he would mean that:\nia> you are a mean person,\nihi you like to think about\nyourself in you are willing\ngive as much as vou take.\n7 The United States lias eight\ngreat rivers. Can you name\nsix of the eight\n8 There is only one well know n\nforeign city of any size\nwhose name begins with the\nletter Z. Where is this city?\nikatmtn oppntiM pm* I\nWhen Peace Comes\nEDITOR'S NOTE \u2014The following selected extractt from the\nopening oddrese delivered to the conference at Mack\ninac !\u2022!and, Mich., by Gov. Maw of Utah, emphaette the great\nand increating part which the etatee of the Federal Union are\ntaking in the whole field of American life:\nBy THE HON7HERBERT B. MAW\nGovernor of Utah\nMORE citizens in all parts of the nation than most of\nus realize are looking to this body to assume leader\nship in the one factor that concerns them most\u2014the res\ntoration of the old freedoms.\nTHEY WANT BUSINESS TO BE FREED FROM\nGOVERNMENT REGULATION, LABOR FROM GOV\nERNMENT REGULATION, THE FARMER FROM\nGOVERNMENT SUPERVISION, AND THE AVERAGE\nCITIZEN FROM RESTRICTIONS WHICH ARE NOT\nCOMPATIBLE WITH FREEDOM AND LIBERTY\nThough they have all been willing to temporarily\nsubmit to whatever regulations were necessary in order\nto win the war\u2014they are concerned over the fact that\nmany federal officials believe and are advocating that our\nnational government should extend into the postwar era\nthe controls and authority exercised by it during the war.\nThe American public does not want any such regula\ntions when peace comes. They, therefore, will sustain\nthis conference in what It does to re-establish our old\nancestral philosophy\u2014that \u201cthat government is best\nwhich governs least.\u2019*\n\nDURING the period of the war the several states have\nmaintained enviable records. They have faithfully\nand efficiently carried out the tasks assigned to them and\nhave proved the effectiveness of state control over pro\ngrams of national scope.\nThe people, through their state and local govern\nments. have made magnificent contributions to the war\nprogram. They conducted salvage drives. They built stock\npiles of rubber, paper, scrap iron and other essential\nmaterials.\nThey organized the rationing machinery. They directed\nthe war fund drives, eliminated trade barriers in order to\nenhance motor truck transportation, organized farm labor\ngroups, created state guards, planned and set up civilian\ndefense units and trained themselves so as to meet the\nvaried emergencies of war.\nAll of these activities and many others were per\nformed mainly through voluntary service and without\nappreciable cost\u2014and they were performed efficiently\nand well.\n\nWHILE the nation has been expending large sums of\nmoney on civilian projects, many of which have\nbeen carried on by the states at small portions of present\ncosts, the states have maintained sound and healthy\nfinancial positions.\nThey have reduced their o\\er-all indebtedness by\nover 25 per cent since 1940.\nThey have invested in government bonds more than\nfour billion dollars of state funds during the past two and\none-hats years, and have created unemployment compen\nsation reserves totaling in excess of six billion dollars. In\naddition, hundreds of millions of dollars have been accu- i\nmulated in other funds by them to provide employment\nopportunities for returning veterans and to give security\nto their citizens when peace comes.\nTHE RECORD MADE BY THE STATES SINCE\nPEARL HARBOR IS ONE OF EFFICIENCY AND\nACHIEVEMENT.\n\nIN THE light of the above, people are giving less and\nless weight to the contention of many theorists that\ncontrol and authority over American life and industry\nshould emanate from Washington and that the states\nshould be required to surrender many of their cherished\nconstitutional prerogatives to federal agencies before\ntheir citizens are allowed to partake of the fruits of con\ngressional legislation.\nMen and women are disco\\ering that the right of\nfree agency is a component part of Americanism, and\nthat without it our government takes on the complexion\nof an autocracy.\nFreedom and Americanism arc synonymous. To the\ncitizens, who through the providence of Almighty God\nhave been permitted to be born in this land, to tb p immi\ngrants who have adopted it as thdlf'*homos, and to for\neigners who, while struggling under the yoke of native\nmagistrates, carry in their hearts dreams of the new\nworld, the two terms have the same meaning. American\nism is freedom.\nIt is the thing our fathers left their native lands to\nfind, for which the war of the revolution was fought, to\nobtain which a record of struggle and privation by the\nfounders of a new' nation was written.\nWITHOUT FREEDOM. INDIVIDUAL FREEDOM.\nINDUSTRIAL FREEDOM. THERE IS NO AMERICAN\nISM.\n\nT TN'DER this conception' of government, the United\nIJ States has grown from a tottering union of 13 states\nto the most powerful nation on earth within the short\nperiod of about 150 years.\nDuring that time all classes of people within its\nborders have enjoyed greater prosperity, more security,\nless fear, and a larger degree of justice than have the\ncitizens of any other nation.\nThis has romp because the people have controlled\ntheir own affairs.\nIt would mean much to the citizens of the nation\nduring these trying times if they could he assured that\nwhen jteare comes the administrative responsibility for\nworking out the postwar adjustments will he put on the\nshoulders of public officials whom the people elect and\nwho respond to the majority will.\nIt would he a tonic to all of us if we could be rtiade to\nfeel that in the years ahead government by the people\nwill continue in this nation and that no system of control\nfrom Washington will replace the simple yet effective\nprocesses that have kept men free.\nKnow lodge* Tost\nRv DR. SABINA CONNOLLY\nfltf# tnirwif OVf for rarh of Ih* flr\u00ab\u00bb\nfit* qo'\u00bbtlont and fl\\ I for lb* I <iur\u00ab.\nlion *rnrr *lO brilliant: 7> bright,\n4 4 arrratr; 0 1, doll\n1 Pntcdam would he a ]r>njj\nwalk from Rrrlin How far\nis if (a\u00bb six miles. ib i 16\nmiles tri 61 miles\n2 The last c7. ar nf the Russians\nwii ctn Pr'i I Nirl\nn! is 11, Alexander III\"\n3- If you\u2019 have a of\nwhtskv, would you bo satis\nfied with iai a quart. (b\u00bb a\npint, lot a Bill\n4 The new director of the\nWoman s Army Corps, CoL\nRoyce, has a martial middle\nname. Is it <at Battle, ib)\nFray, fc) Mars\u2019\n5-The Polish author best\nknown in the English world\nis- far Victor Hugo. ih>\nJoseph Conrad, <c* Leo Tol\nstoi\n6 These are all scrambled\nnames of presidents of the\nUnited States. Name each\none. (a) Digccnlo. ibi Tan\ngishwon. tc) Clinnol, id>\nSadmoni (e) Hidrang\n(.Answer* on opposite page)\nWestbrook\nI'EGLER\n\u2014Fair\nEnough\nRETURNING to the dehats\nv on the proposition that\nmembers of the family of th\u00aej\nlate President Roosevelt com\nmercialized the presidency, this\nis to recall a radio program\npromoted by a group of candy\nmanufacture rs who, in 1942,\nwere apprehensive lest candy b\u00ae\ndeclared nonessential.\nLike many other business in\nterests, they were on the bor\nderline and might he ruled out\non the ground that the ingredi\nents which they used were\nbetter used as food in the ordi\nnary sense of the word and\ntheir people and pfiants better\nemployed otherwise.\nJoseph W. Hicks, a public\nrelations genius, was engaged\nto find a way, and presently\ncame up with a device called\nthe Council of Candy as Food\nin the War FfTort.\nThe firm of Bat ton, Barton,\nDurst me and Osborne was en\ngaged to,handle the advertising.\nBetween them they appear to\nhave done a good job. for,\nwhether we agree that candy\nhas been a food essential to tht\nwar effort, the candy industry\nhas lived on\n\nEARNEST K. LINDLEY. a\nJ Washington journalist and\nsympathetic interpreter of tha\nNew Deal, was engaged as th*\nnews commentator for a radio\nprogram of 52 weeks\nHis wife, Mrs Betty Lindley,\nan intimate friend of Mrs.\nRoosevelt, was hired to help\narrange the programs.\nIn an earlier venture Mrs.\nLindley had represented Mrs.\nRoosevelt in negotiations for a\nseason as commentator for the\nTan-American Coffee Rureau in\na program financed through th*\npublic ta\\e\u00ab of number of\nLatin-American republics\nThe Council on Candy as\nFood wanted b:g names in\nacceptance of the principle\npropounded hv the Buchanan\nagency another advertising\nfirm, in offering Mrs Ron*p\\e|t\nas ft radio attraction in the\ncoffee program\nThe Buchanan agency railed\nthis the follow the leader'*\nprinciple and it has been vindi\ncated by adverti-ers not only\nin the United States but. ear\nher. in Great Britain, where the\nt tie of \"purveyor'* of chutney,\nkippers nr bear grease for the\nhair to their majesties wa\u00ab a\nvaluable commercial boast long\nbefore American advertiser*\ntook to buying testimonial* for\ncigarets from athletes who d 1\n.not smoke\nThe randy manufacturers also\nwanted names and they got\nHenry Wallace and Paul Me-\nNutt, generals and admirals for\ntheir radio program and wera\nwe|| pleased wi\u2019h the results.\nThese individuals made no\ncharge for their service*.\n\nIN THE course of this v.rH'.nn\nMrs Poosevelt made two\nappearances of eight minute*\neach at a fee of $l 300 ;v*r\nbroadcast nr ius* ahoijt SJOO a\nn nu\u2019e and m\\ authority, who\nhad a part in the arrangements,\nunderstands ihat there was a\nthird broadcast at 82.500\nWhat Mrs Roosevelt did w i'h\n*he money is something that\nshe has always deemed to he\nher own business, although\nthere ha\\e been suggestions\nvoted to p .rpnse*\nwhich wej-e called chantie\u00ae\nA press handout dated Dec.\n191 J. from the offices of the\ncouncil said Mrs Franklin D.\nRoosevelt will give a report to\nthe mo*hers of the nation on\nher rerent trip to England in\na roast to toast broadcast\ndnr-dav evening Dec 9 Th*\nprogram v< ,11 be presumed bv\nthe Council on Candy as Food\nin the War FfTort\n\nVO MENTION w is made of a\nfee to Mrs fop\nsuch a report to the mothers\nof the nation. although that\nwould seem to have been ap\npropnate information for lack\nof which it may have been as\nsumed that she was making this\nreport free a\u00ab a generous service\nto those mothers\nMoreover, their was no -ug\ngrstinn that Mis Roosevelt paid\nany pait of her expenses on this\ntr p which thus vr assumed to\nhave been borne by either the\nRed Cross or the taxpayers.\nNo question i- raised here as\nto the legality of the conduct of\nMr and Mrs Lindley but if I\nhad ever accepted a similar as\nsignment and compensation\nfrom. sav. Torn Girdler of Re\npublic Steel, who fought and\nheat President Roosevelt's CIO,\nthe journalists of the New Deal\nwould have called my fee a\nbrass check\nAnd. if Mrs Tom Dewey had\nundertaken a radio program for\npay and the wife of some ag\ngressive anti-N\u2019ew Deal journal\nist had been engaged profitably\nas agent that would have been\nffenoutlrrd as a snhtlp manner\nof paving for tl favorable\nopinion of the writer\nRut did Mrs Roo evelf her\u00ae\ncommercialize the presidency?\nthe answer to that is another\nquestion Why did the Council\non Candy as Food select her?\nDutnbutwl by King Fuuiw i\u00dffc","height":"27774","width":"21282"}}
